  "text": "The measurements of body weight and body composition also demonstrate that AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ /Tbc1d1 Ϫ/Ϫ mice match AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ mice better. But body weights of male AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ / Tbc1d1 Ϫ/Ϫ mice track with reduced weights for both male AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ and Tbc1d1 Ϫ/Ϫ mice (Fig. 1A) 6A) [CITATION_1] , which may only partially be compensated by increased food intake ( Fig. 6B) [CITATION_2] and decreased activity (AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ mice only; Fig. 6D ). The earlier study with singleand double-AS160 and Tbc1d1-knockout mice on a chow diet did not evaluate energy expenditure, food intake, or activity [CITATION_3] . Previous studies showed increased resting metabolic rates in high-fat diet-fed Tbc1d1 Ϫ/Ϫ mice (9) but decreased oxygen consumption and heat production in chow-fed AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ mice (36). We did not observe any abnormalities in RER in male single-or double-AS160 and Tbc1d1-knockout mice (Fig. 6 ) [CITATION_4] . But earlier, we observed decreased RER in female Tbc1d1 Ϫ/Ϫ mice and increased fatty acid oxidation in male and female Tbc1d1",
